node.text:
Awesome post by @leo.jeanlouis 🔥

Lifestyle creep or lifestyle inflation is the tendency for people to increase their spending as their earnings increase.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
For example, let’s say Jessica’s take-home pay last year was $3,500/month. This year she got a raise and her take-home pay increased to $3,800. After getting this raise, Jessica felt like she needed to move into a newer apartment closer to downtown with a higher rent and dine out for brunch and dinner every weekend because she “deserves it”. Instead of using that $300 to get closer to her goals, she increased her spending as things that were once luxuries all of a sudden became “necessities” in her mind. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
She made an extra $300 but spent an extra $300. In reality, she never really got a raise!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Had she used that extra $300 to pay off debt, she could have saved herself hundred of thousands of dollars in interest payments and bought her freedom back by shaving YEARS off of her timeline to pay off her debt!
⁣⁣
Had she used that extra $300 to invest it, she could have grown her net worth by over $300k over the next 30 years, assuming a 7% ROI!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Moral of the story? Avoid lifestyle creep!!⁣⁣

Give my friend @leo.jeanlouis a follow if you’re looking to learn more about personal finance!!
High Income + Low cost lifestyle = Massive wealth building potential

Stock market sales are a long term investors best friend. 

If you’re investing for the next 10-20+ years, short term market sales give you an opportunity to add to your portfolio at a cheaper price! Learn to see market pull backs as a buying opportunity, not a fearful event! 💯🔥

Now of course this projection would assume you (or your kid) would continue to invest the $416 per month well after they’ve left the nest, but still shows how powerful investing early and often can be! 

The younger someone is, the more time they have to allow their investment to grow in the stock market. 

Opening a custodial account and investing on behalf of your kid can put them miles ahead and allow them the opportunity to focus on things that they really want to do in life. (Just don’t forget to pass down the financial knowledge as well)

node.text: The key to a happier life 💯🔥
Wayyyy too common 😂 let the people who actually have a million say if they think it’s nothing or not
Be that person. Do it for your future self and family. 💯🔥

This is a common strategy that some wealthy people use to avoid selling stocks directly and having to pay capital gains taxes. 

People who use this strategy take advantage of low interest loans some brokerages offer and “pay them back” by making sure the loan is lower than the average appreciation of the asset they are borrowing against. 

As long as your investments/dividends are covering the interest of the loans, you’d be set. 

Definitely make sure to talk with a tax professional and do your own research before doing anything like this yourself. This post is just to bring awareness around this tax strategy.
